<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<%- include('/partials/head') %>
</head>
<body>

<%- include('/partials/header') %>

<section class="page-head">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="grid">
      <div class="eyebrow-wrap"><span class="eyebrow">FAQ</span></div>
      <div>
        <div class="crumbs"><a href="<%= rootPath %>">Home</a> &nbsp;/&nbsp; <span>FAQ</span></div>
        <h1>Before you <em>visit</em>.</h1>
        <p class="lead">A few answers for visitors from abroad — on etiquette, accessibility, what to expect, and what a small Buddhist temple actually is. If your question isn't answered here, please get in touch.</p>
        <div class="jp-sub">よくあるご質問</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="faq-section">
  <div class="wrap">

    <!-- Group 1: Visiting basics -->
    <div class="faq-group">
      <div class="label">
        <span class="num">I — Basics</span>
        <h3>Visiting the temple</h3>
        <span class="jp">参拝について</span>
      </div>
      <div class="qs faq-list">
        <details open>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">01</span>
            <span class="q-text">Can non-Buddhists and foreign visitors enter the temple?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>Yes — all are welcome during open hours (7:00 — 17:00), regardless of background or belief. No reservation is needed, and there is no admission fee. You are welcome to walk the grounds, sit quietly in the main hall, or simply pass through on your way up the hillside.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">02</span>
            <span class="q-text">Do I need to pay to enter?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>No. Entry to the grounds and the main hall is free. A small offering box (<em>saisen-bako</em>) sits in front of the altar if you wish to give — a coin of any denomination is fine.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">03</span>
            <span class="q-text">How long does a visit usually take?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>A quiet walk through the grounds takes about 30 minutes. If you would like to sit in the main hall or read the plaques along the way, budget an hour. A full guided tour (by appointment) is roughly 90 minutes.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">04</span>
            <span class="q-text">Can I reach the temple on foot from Shin-Kobe Station?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>Yes. It is a 15-minute walk — mostly flat, with a short climb at the end. From Sannomiya Station it is about 25 minutes on foot, or 10 minutes by taxi. See the map on the home page for the route.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Group 2: Etiquette -->
    <div class="faq-group">
      <div class="label">
        <span class="num">II — Etiquette</span>
        <h3>Inside the hall</h3>
        <span class="jp">作法・マナー</span>
      </div>
      <div class="qs faq-list">
        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">05</span>
            <span class="q-text">Is there etiquette I should follow inside the hall?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>Nothing strict. Please remove your shoes at the step before the main hall — slippers are provided. Speak softly, keep phones on silent, and feel free to place your palms together (<em>gasshō</em>) before the altar if you wish.</p>
            <p>You do not need to chant, bow, or follow any particular form. Sitting quietly is itself a kind of practice.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">06</span>
            <span class="q-text">Can I take photographs?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>Photography is welcome throughout the grounds. Inside the main hall please refrain from using flash, and avoid photographing worshippers or ceremonies in progress. If a service is underway, it is best to wait until it is over.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">07</span>
            <span class="q-text">Is there a dress code?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>No formal dress code. Casual clothing is fine; we simply ask that shoulders and knees be reasonably covered, especially inside the main hall. Easily-removed shoes are helpful, as you will take them off before entering.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Group 3: Accessibility & support -->
    <div class="faq-group">
      <div class="label">
        <span class="num">III — Practical</span>
        <h3>Accessibility &amp; support</h3>
        <span class="jp">アクセシビリティ・対応</span>
      </div>
      <div class="qs faq-list">
        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">08</span>
            <span class="q-text">Is the temple wheelchair-accessible?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>Yes. A continuous, gently climbing ramp leads from the street-level entrance up to the second and third floors, with a lift connecting the ground floor to the upper halls. Visitors with limited mobility are welcome to ring the bell at the lower entrance for assistance.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">09</span>
            <span class="q-text">Are there English-speaking guides or materials?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>The temple office can usually answer questions in simple English during office hours (9:00 — 17:00). For a fuller tour or to meet the head priest, please email or phone in advance — a few days' notice is ideal. Written materials in English are available on request.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">10</span>
            <span class="q-text">Is there a café or a place to sit?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>The temple recently opened a small in-house dining room, <em>Sekai</em>, currently by reservation for groups only. Benches sit along the koi garden and beside the main hall — a good spot to rest after the climb.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Group 4: Faith & ceremonies -->
    <div class="faq-group">
      <div class="label">
        <span class="num">IV — Practice</span>
        <h3>Faith &amp; ceremonies</h3>
        <span class="jp">信仰・法要</span>
      </div>
      <div class="qs faq-list">
        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">11</span>
            <span class="q-text">What is Nichiren-shū? How is it different from other Buddhist schools?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>Nichiren-shū is one of the major schools of Japanese Buddhism, founded in the 13th century by Nichiren Shōnin. Its practice centres on the Lotus Sūtra and the chanted phrase <em>Namu Myōhō Renge Kyō</em>.</p>
            <p>Read more on our <a href="<%= rootPath %>about/">About</a> page.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">12</span>
            <span class="q-text">Can I attend a ceremony or memorial service?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>Most regular services are open to quiet observation — there is no need to register. Monthly observances and major annual ceremonies are also streamed on our <a href="https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCNAaxCyBY_0nOeElQppw3AQ/live?app=desktop" target="_blank" rel="noopener">YouTube channel</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">13</span>
            <span class="q-text">I'd like to request a memorial or prayer service. Is that possible?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>Yes — we accept requests for memorial services (<em>hōyō</em>), prayer rites (<em>kitō</em>), and ancestor offerings from anyone, regardless of denomination or nationality. Please contact the office at least two weeks in advance to arrange a time.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            <span class="q-num">14</span>
            <span class="q-text">Can I bring children?</span>
            <span class="q-plus"></span>
          </summary>
          <div class="q-body">
            <p>Of course. Children are welcome on the grounds and in the main hall. The koi garden in particular is a favourite — a quiet space to walk and watch the fish.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- contact strip -->
    <div class="contact-strip">
      <div>
        <h3>Still have a <em>question</em>?</h3>
        <p>If your question isn't answered here, the temple office is the best place to start. We respond in simple English during office hours, and can usually arrange a guided visit with a few days' notice.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info">
        <div class="row"><span>Telephone</span><strong>078-575-2608</strong></div>
        <div class="row"><span>Office hours</span><strong>09:00 — 17:00</strong></div>
        <div class="row"><span>Open daily</span><strong>07:00 — 17:00</strong></div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

<%- include('/partials/footer') %>

<script src="<%= rootPath %>site.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
